hands_on_practices.solution:
We work in coordinates $x^\mu=(T,X,\theta,\phi)$ with metric
$$g_{TT}=-A(r),\quad g_{XX}=A(r),\quad A(r)=\frac{32(GM)^3}{r}e^{-r/(2GM)},$$
and all other $g_{\mu\nu}$ diagonal.  The only nonzero contribution to
$$\Gamma^X_{TT}
=\tfrac12\,g^{X\sigma}\bigl(2\partial_Tg_{\sigma T}-\partial_\sigma g_{TT}\bigr)$$
comes from $\sigma=X$:
$$\Gamma^X_{TT}
=-\tfrac12\,g^{XX}\,\partial_Xg_{TT}
=\frac1{2A(r)}\;A'(r)\,\partial_Xr.$$

1. Compute $A'(r)$:
$$A'(r)
=32(GM)^3\frac{d}{dr}\Bigl(r^{-1}e^{-r/(2GM)}\Bigr)
=-32(GM)^3r^{-2}e^{-r/(2GM)}\Bigl(1+\frac r{2GM}\Bigr),$$
so
$$\frac{A'(r)}{2A(r)}
=-\frac{1}{2}\frac{1+\frac r{2GM}}{r}
=-\Bigl(\frac1{2r}+\frac1{4GM}\Bigr).$$

2. Differentiate the defining relation
$$F(r,T,X)=X^2-T^2-\Bigl(\frac r{2GM}-1\Bigr)e^{r/(2GM)}=0$$
w.r.t. $X$:
$$\partial_Xr=-\frac{\partial_XF}{\partial_rF}
=-\frac{2X}{-\frac{r}{4G^2M^2}e^{r/(2GM)}}
=\frac{8G^2M^2\,X}{r\,e^{r/(2GM)}}.$$

3. Hence
$$\Gamma^X_{TT}
=-\Bigl(\frac1{2r}+\frac1{4GM}\Bigr)\,
\frac{8G^2M^2X}{r\,e^{r/(2GM)}}
=-\frac{2GM\,(r+2GM)\,X}{r^2\,e^{r/(2GM)}}.$$
